“Therefore, let us keep the feast. Alleluia!”

Whether it’s communion, Christmas dinner, or a PB&J wrapped in a paper towel, there is a feast to be kept. A soulful feast to be kept for sustenance, in turn, kept to be then be shared. 

Keeping for sharing. Complements that truly work together. I love salty and sweet. Red with green. A silent night, but with angels - thousands of angels - sent simply for shepherds. Hark!

The magi with gold for a baby, and a king born in a stable. The Christmas story is glory in the highest, and away in a manger. A feast of complementary expressions for our lives. Merry and bright, yet blue… memories of love and lives lost amidst sparkle and twinkle. 

I always quote my Mimi who instilled in me that we “eat with our eyes first. But more importantly, we feed people - body and soul - from our tables.” 

Keeping the feast - nourish to flourish - grow to share, go forth in the law of love and gospel of peace. That’s the charge given to us after communion with one another. Keep the feast and rejoice! After all, that’s what alleluia means! Rejoice! 

Repeat the sounding joy! 

🌺 @marigolddesign 
📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer 
🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc

“Light and life to all He brings…” Hark! 

It’s the shortest day of the year, yet the longest night. Isn’t it amazing that for centuries, we chant and sing about light? Pray and hope for light? Hymns and carols, scriptures and creeds… bring a torch, follow a star or, if need be, look up, my fellow shepherds, at the sky lit and filled with heavenly hosts! 

Light is constantly piercing the darkness, metaphorically and actually in our lives. As my favorite Robert Frost poem mentions, it is “the darkest evening of the year.”

Yet… there’s always audacious hope. A silver lining in that the days now become longer - inching towards another solstice and season of brighter light. Minute by minute, morning by morning - Light from Light… after all, “let there be light” commenced and began creation - and here’s the bonus - followed by a garden! 

Back to light and life - hark that herald, indeed! Repeat the sounding joy! 

Yet, I must admit to sometimes being more of a Ouiser than a Clairee this time of year. “I’M PLEASANT!” It can happen. 

Using Mama’s Christmas china, Mimi’s silver, recalling Grandaddy’s sermons and humor… craving Light from Light on the darkest evening of the year. Love lost yet enduring. 

The charge and benediction to all this brings me back to the seasons, to celebrations of home, to longer days - warmer days - and to keeping the feast and passing the peace! 

It may be the longest night - but it can be Oh Holy Night - and oh night divine! 

Wishing us all comfort and joy - whether it’s a “Blue Christmas” or a “Holly Jolly” one! May we be merry and bright all season long! 

🌺 @marigolddesign 
📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer 
🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc

Over Christmas, a freeze descended so far southward, that wells froze, citrus groves were zapped and camellias starting their season were frozen, halting their blooming. Record cold temps were broken and reset. Three days later, we were sunny and 75. That’s life in Georgia!

And from Christmas to a New Year, life marches onward to a cadence and rhythm all of its own - even within the span of a few days. This year was monumental for so many of us - and yet just another year for others. I can’t help but be thankful for a good year. Not without its turmoil, though. 

I can’t help but reflect this last week of the year is a snippet - a mimicry - of the year as whole. Ultimately good and hope secured - I count the year a joyful and delightful - not without the balance of loss and grief. 

Starting with the delight, warmth and anticipation of Christmas, the week turned cold - a cold that robbed us of greenery and garden life.  Symbolic of the last year indeed. This year brought great love and great loss of love. Life and death dueled - dear friends were lost, and new babies cried with their first breath of life. Freezes and thaws, cold then sun, summer and winter, spring and fall. Soon the sun shone again, the well thawed, and a New Year was on the horizon and dawning. And, yet, the year left a wake of thankfulness and peace. 

I noticed today, that my camellias are going to rebound. They are going to bloom with audacious hope in the midst of winter. 

Camellias represent love, affection, and admiration. Pink camellias represent longing -the missing of a loved one, the longing for new love and life, or perhaps just longing for a New Year. Red camellias represent love and passion. White camellias stand for purity and innocence. 

2022 was quite a year. And as the year 2023 commences, I want to be surrounded by “camellias.” Harbingers of hope. I want to long for the promise of goodness and be passionate for the purity of beauty and love - even in the midst of winter. 

Bloom and grow - flourish and nourish yourselves in our homes and gardens, and may Celebrating Home be your privilege and delight this New Year! 🌸🌺

📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer 
🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc

A song with all the feels! I love it! 

I adore those wintry days of crisp chill, sunshine warming just enough and the architecture of the landscape is evident. Blue bird skies - Carolina blue in Cashiers - with sparks of green, white and gray amidst the laurels and rocks and ridge lines. 

A tinge of tangerine will set the mountains aglow at sunset, and the bright, full moon shines somewhat brighter up in those mountains - especially though the bare branches. 

This was the inspiration for a winter dinner - seen in Celebrating Home. Refreshing from the heaviness of the holidays, I embrace my summertime motto of “green and white is always right” for this wintry supper. @molliejenkinspottery dinnerware and @gardenerscottageasheville florals help capture the season in my dining room at Joe Pye Cottage. I love wintertime in the mountains - gathering with friends around the hearth and table, warming up with food and fellowship, and celebrating the season. 

Each day mercifully is a minute or so longer - the promise of spring to come. But, candles and votives and fireplaces help to keep the feast, nonetheless, this time of year. Celebrate your season, your home, your friends and family any chance you can! 

🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc 
📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer 
🌿 @gardenerscottageasheville 
🍽️ @molliejenkinspottery

It’s the best day! February 9, 2016, I was honored beyond measure to donate a kidney to @meredithfarmerdeal !! After a childhood illness, we knew she would need a kidney one day, and that day was at hand seven years ago. 

I am working on a special project and have been writing about this story - my favorite story to tell! As y’all know, I love to tell a good story, but this one is truly my favorite! Ordained miracles and appointments, angels here in earth, incredible science and miraculous discoveries all meld into a story gifted to us to share - and celebrate! 

The encouragement I want to extend today and every single day is to give… my grandparents used to tell us we can give time, talent, or treasure… Whatever we have! And I know that we may not all be able to give kidneys, we can give something of ourselves. Please give blood. Please give time to someone who may need a minute… share your talents, and treasure is more than money. 

Trust me, giving IS the best gift! I know there is a benefit to the beneficiary but being a “cheerful giver” will delight you more than words can say! Oh happy day! 

@meredithfarmerdeal @provvista_designs @smyelton

The @jamesfarmerinc design team is busy with some wonderful projects. And sat down to look back at some past pieces that still give us all the heart eyes and starry ones, too! Over the course of the holiday season, I’ll share some of my favorite pieces we use on our projects. Timeless and traditional pieces but with a twist for today! 

Mahogany, burled woods, tones and patina - the colors and textures and handsome proportions make the secretary one of my favorite pieces of furniture. 

Useful and handy, elegant and stately, these pieces work in just about any room! From foyers to bathrooms, dining rooms and bedrooms, I love to place a secretary for form and function. Topped with jars or demijohns, vases or baskets, these pieces truly make a wonderful addition to any room! 

I encourage y’all to use antiques. Buy them and treasure them. Pair them with contemporary pieces and used them each day!

I scream, you scream, we all scream for a fabulous SCREEN! Next up in this series of antiques and fun finds, is the ever-delightful screen! 

From backdrops to focal points, works of art in and of themselves, we @jamesfarmerinc LOVE to use a screen! Their original purposes as, well, a screen, aren’t always in demand, but truly displayed now as artwork is a stunning way to show off their character. 

Lacquer or leather tooled, painted and pierced - we love a gorgeous screen behind a sofa, atop a mantelpiece or anchoring a wall in a large room. Screens are old guard mixed media, classic yet fresh, and often the inspiration for a room! 

Keep your eyes peeled for them at antique shops, estate sales and even commissions, too, by fantastic artists for today! They tell a story of life in artistic expression, and a wonderful screen is always in demand for my design team and me. 

📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer and @jeffherrphoto

Next up on using antiques in today’s designs… you guessed it! Plates! 

One of my Mimi’s friends hired me when I graduated from Auburn to “help” her with her dining room and living room. 

I was standing on a ladder hanging plates, and I overheard her talking to my grandmother, “Yes, he’s here and hanging plates on the wall!” 😂😂😂 Some things never change! 

From plates to platters, brackets and sconces and antlers mixed therein, I love to display plates on a wall! Especially sets we may, perhaps, no longer use for dining - this display and array gives them new light and purpose! Exquisite art in and of themselves, I love dessert sets, fish sets and serving platters all together as an accent on the wall or as the main stage! 

So, here’s a smattering of platters and plates to inspire and delight! 

📸 @jeffherrphoto and @emilyfollowillphotographer 
🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc

Up next in this series of antiques for today… the workhouse of every and any room, a classic piece yesterday, today and tomorrow, waxed or burled, painted or stained, English, French, Italian and everywhere in between… a chest! Give me George III or Louis Philippe any ol’ day! 

Bowfront, box, bedside or banded, a chest is perfect in nearly any scenario. Mahogany bowfronts or painted French commodes to handsome Italians, a chest will serve its purpose and be there for you and your next generations, too! 

Pair them with mirrors, paintings, art and stacks of books and lamps, too!  Use them! They make excellent storage pieces… Fancy that? Using something for its intended purpose… cherished pieces now and forever!

But besides that, we love to use them in fresh ways as well! They can make a great bar, serving piece or anchor to the end of a hallway. A “go-to” in any instance! We @jamesfarmerinc always think a chest is best! 

🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc 
📸 @jeffherrphoto  and @emilyfollowillphotographer

Next up on my series of statement pieces and design staples for the @jamesfarmerinc team… lampshades! Not just any lampshades… custom patterned and custom made shades that make any lamp a true work of art! 

A little history with lampshades - they did not start out as white drums! They had stained glass, silk pleats, patterns and colors and sensational styles! From Tiffany and Co glass to woven reeds and glass globes to empire silks pleated to painted ones of every genre, lampshades were never intended to be boring! 

Granted we do love a classic shade, we love pizazz and punch, too! All of our lampshades are custom for our lamps - which I believe no good lamp started life as a lamp! 

Feeling crafty, hot glue some cording or a zippy tape! Makes all the difference! From plaids to prints, linen to silk, to tole and metal - we love a fabulous lampshade!! 

🖼️ @jamesfarmerinc 
📸 @emilyfollowillphotographer and @jeffherrphoto

“Lee Jofa’s Tree of Life is absolutely one of my favorite fabrics. When I was young, I even started a “Tree of Life Fund” for myself to save up for it…and it’s what I have in my bedroom to this day! It contains nearly every color, making it so versatile when designing a room. With the recent introduction of the Tree of Life wallpaper, I decided it was the perfect direction for the Flower  Magazine Baton Rouge Showhouse. Using it for the wallcovering and dining chair fabric gave the room a warm, bold and colorful feel. I pulled the greens and blues from the pattern for details and paint colors but also blended bright artwork to freshen up the space. Now, if only I could host a dinner party there, it would be perfect!” @jamestfarmer
